text.caption:
Ring Participants screen(s) provides an ordered list of ring nodes (up to a 40 node network) starting with the Supervisor node, then out to the network on Port 1, and return back on Port 2. Each node is displayed with its IP (if available) and MAC addresses.
FYI: Participants information is only accurate when the DLR network is in normal condition. When there is a fault on the network, this information may no longer be accurate. Thus, the Ring Participants screen is programmatically controlled to hide when there is a ring fault. To disable this behavior, please refer to the documentation for this faceplate.

text.name: Text52
text.caption:
The following fault conditions are captured by the faceplate and are displayed on the Alarm Status screen:
- Message instruction fault: press the “Reset MSG” button to reset errored MSG instructions.
- Ring fault location: IP and MAC addresses of the adjacent nodes next to the fault are reported.
- Rapid ring fault & restore cycles: condition is true when 5 or more faults occurred within 30 sec. Press the “CLR Rapid Faults” button to return the network back to normal.
For additional information about these errors, refer to the EtherNet/IP Embedded Switch Technology Application Guide.

text.name: ConfigHelpTitle_Text1
text.caption: Help - Network Status Overview & Supervisor Info

text.name: Text53
text.caption:
This is an EtherNet/IP Device Level Ring (DLR) diagnostics faceplate. This information is retrieved from the Ring Supervisor node on the network.
The Ring Supervisor’s Precedence value determines which supervisor-enabled node is the active supervisor. The node with the highest value is the supervisor.
Ring Supervisor – Port Status Information screen contains configuration and status indicators of the Ethernet ports on the supervisor node. Note: 1756-EN2TR has two ports and 1783-ETAP has three ports. 1783-ETAP also has Port Buffer Utilization indicators.
For more information, refer to the EtherNet/IP Embedded Switch Technology Application Guide.
